{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606992"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15944"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15944"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8635"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8702"},{"type":"tags","id":"8704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pituitary gland develops from two distinct embryological sources. The anterior and posterior portions have different developmental origins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the posterior pituitary gland?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neural crest cells from the hindbrain","Surface ectoderm from Rathke pouch","Endoderm from the primitive gut","Neural ectoderm from the diencephalon","Mesoderm from the notochord"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis) develops as a downward growth of \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural ectoderm from the diencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E of the developing brain. This forms the infundibulum (infundibular stalk) which gives rise to the posterior pituitary and maintains its connection to the hypothalamus throughout development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells from the hindbrain\u003C/strong\u003E - While neural crest cells give rise to many structures, they do not contribute to pituitary development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface ectoderm from Rathke pouch\u003C/strong\u003E - This actually gives rise to the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoderm from the primitive gut\u003C/strong\u003E - The primitive gut gives rise to the gastrointestinal tract and associated organs, not the pituitary\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesoderm from the notochord\u003C/strong\u003E - The notochord induces neural tube formation but does not directly contribute to pituitary tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe connection between the posterior pituitary and hypothalamus via the infundibular stalk is crucial for the transport and release of oxytocin and vasopressin, which are produced in the hypothalamus but stored and released from the posterior pituitary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The posterior pituitary gland (neurohypophysis) develops as a downward growth from the diencephalon of the neural ectoderm.","The posterior pituitary remains connected to the hypothalamus via the infundibular stalk throughout development.","The anterior pituitary develops separately from Rathke pouch, which originates from oral cavity ectoderm."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015","Scott IS, Chattopadhyay A, Ansorge O. Development and Microscopic Anatomy of the Pituitary Gland. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com. [Updated 2024 Sep 28]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK425703/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15944"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:59:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T10:00:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8635"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"t